      <div xml:id="NA72-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi ciṟaippuṟamākat talaivikku uraippāḷāyc colliyatu.
            (ETv: kuṟai nērnta tōḻi talaivi kuṟai nayappa kūriyatu.)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said as one who is talking to HER while [HE] was behind the fence.
            (ETv: What the confidante, who had agreed to [his] request, said so that SHE would grant [his] request.)</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA72">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            pēṇupa pēṇār periyō reṉpatu</l>
<l>            nāṇuttak kaṉṟatu kāṇuṅ kālai</l>
<l>            yuyirō raṉṉa ceyirtīr naṭpi</l>
<l>            ṉiṉakkiyāṉ maṟaittal yāvatu mikapperi</l>
<l>            taḻitak kaṉṟāṟ ṟāṉē koṇkaṉ </l>
<l>            yāṉyā yañcuva leṉiṉun tāṉē</l>
<l>            pirital cūḻāṉ maṉṉē yiṉiyē</l>
<l>            kāṉa lāya maṟiyiṉu māṉā</l>
<l>            talarva taṉṟuko leṉṉu mataṉāṟ</l>
<l>            pularvatu kollavaṉ naṭpeṉa </l>
<l>            vañcuva ṟōḻiyeṉ ṉeñcat tāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>For saying “great ones may either value it or not”<note place="foot">T.V.G. reads <term xml:lang="ta">pēṇupa</term> not as a finite verb, but as an participial noun n.pl.: 'the things to be esteemed', that is, 'the doctrines to be followed'. So either great people do not heed them, or it is two finite verbs in sequence, then giving the meaning that great ones will either do one or the other, one cannot be sure. The point is in any case that one of the women has doubted HIS integrity, and the other one tells her off; actually I think SHE is talking to the confidante.</note></l>
<l>shame is fitting<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">takkaṉṟu</term>: here and in line 5 it is impossible to render the perfective aspect in the translation, unless with a quite heavy „it has come to be fitting".</note>, when one looks at it.<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kāṇum kālai</term>: this is one of the definition phrases well-known from the theoretical literature. The implication in this context might be that the thing stated is something obvious.</note></l>
<l>Very great desolation is what is fitting indeed</l>
<l>for my not concealing anything from you</l>
<l>about the flawless intimacy just like life.</l>
<l>Even if I said<note place="foot">This sentence with <term xml:lang="ta">eṉiṉum</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">cūḻāṉ</term> in itself does not give a hint as to the temporary sequence, but since the next sentence starts with iṉi "now", we might feel entitled to interpret this one in a sense of anteriority.</note> to the man from the sea “I fear mother”,</l>
<l>as for him, he certainly wouldn't consider separating.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Now,</l>
<l>even if [just my] companions know of the seashore-grove,</l>
<l>he(?) says “that [is] unending gossip, isn't it?”</l>
<l rend="indent4">Therefore,</l>
<l>“is it drying up, his friendship?”,</l>
<l>[so] I fear, friend, in my heart.</l>
        </lg>
